SIMPLE: wraith
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wraith
<hw>Wraith</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Scot.
<ets>wraith</ets>, <ets>warth</ets>; probably originally, a guardian
angel, from Icel. <ets>v⟦oum⟧r⟦edh⟧r</ets> a warden, guardian, akin to
E. <ets>ward</ets>. See <er>Ward</er> a guard.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>An apparition of a person in his exact likeness,
seen before death, or a little after; hence, an apparition; a specter; a
vision; an unreal image.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She was uncertain if it were the gypsy or her
<qex>wraith</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O, hollow <qex>wraith</qex> of dying fame.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Sometimes, improperly, a spirit thought to preside
over the waters; -- called also <altname>water wraith</altname>.</def>
<rj><au>M. G. Lewis.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wrangle</ent>⟦br⟧
